HF Company, JCDecaux, Maisons France, Safran, Sanofi: French Stock Preview

-- B y   V i d y a   R o o t   a n d   P h i l   S e r a f i n o
-- 
2011-05-10T03:30:05Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-09/jcdecaux-maisons-france-safran-thales-french-stock-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose stocks may have unusual changes in Paris. Symbols are in
parentheses after company names and prices are from the last
close.  France’s  CAC 40 Index (CAC)  fell 50.75 points, or 1.3 percent, to
4,007.26 in Paris. The broader SBF 120 Index declined 1.1
percent to 3,015.09 points.  Avenir Telecom (AVT)  SA: The distributor of mobile
telecommunications equipment said revenue for the year ended
March 31 slid to 563 million euros from 571 million euros at
constant exchange rates. The shares fell 2.7 percent to 1.07
euros.  BNP Paribas (BNP)  : The company plans to announce at the
annual shareholder meeting on May 11 that Chairman Michel
Pebereau will retire by next year and be replaced by Chief
Executive Officer Baudouin Prot, the Financial Times reported,
without saying where it got the information. Deputy CEO Jean-
Laurent Bonnafe will succeed Prot, the newspaper reported. The
stock fell 1.49 euros, or 2.7 percent, to 52.94 euros.  Credit Agricole Ile de France (CAF)  : The regional
banking unit of Credit Agricole SA for the Paris area said
first-quarter net income rose 17 percent to 84 million euros.
The shares slid 0.1 percent to 61.61 euros.  HF Company (HF FP): The maker of receivers and transmitters
of high-frequency signals said it sees a “slight” profit in
the first half after material costs rose. The company said it
plans to raise prices to offset higher costs. The shares fell
5.7 percent to 14.62 euros.  JCDecaux SA (DEC)  : The world’s second-largest seller of
outdoor advertising had first-quarter revenue of 535.3 million
euros, compared with 487.2 million euros a year earlier, the
company said in an e-mailed statement. Shares rose 1.2 percent
to 23.15 euros.  Maisons France Confort (MFC)  : The French home builder
said first-quarter revenue rose 54 percent to 139.8 million
euros and it sees “excellent” full-year operating
profitability. The shares fell 0.2 percent to 36.25 euros.  Safran SA (SAF)   and  Thales SA (HO)  : The companies may
agree by the summer on swapping military assets, the head of
France’s defense procurement agency said, according to  Les Echos .
Safran would own businesses that make inertial-navigation and
electric-generation equipment, and Thales would get the
optoelectronics operation, the newspaper reported, citing
Laurent Collet-Billon, head of the Delegation Generale pour
l’Armement. Safran fell 0.4 percent to 26 euros and Thales lost
0.2 percent to 29.71 euros.  Sanofi (SAN FP): The French pharmaceutical company’s Chief
Executive Officer Chris Viehbacher said it aims to expand its
animal health business, Merial, which will seek to make
acquisitions, though “probably not of significant size,”
following the  unravelling  of its joint venture with Merck & Co.,
the Financial Times reported, citing an interview. The stock
fell 0.5 percent to 54.96 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Vidya Root in Paris at 
 vroot@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Tim Quinson at 
 tquinson@bloomberg.net . 